Cables Exploration

This is an exploration of declassified cables. An sqlite database cables.db holds the relevant data.

Message Frequency

Let’s start by looking at the frequency of messages over time, colored by the day of the week.

Immediately we notice low activity on weekends, with the lowest number of cables being sent on Sundays. Looking at this through another lens, we see the following.

We can also examine message frequency based on month or year.

This brings to mind several questions.

  • Are the messages being sent on the weekends more important/urgent?
  • Do different locations prefer to send messages at different times? (e.g Saturday may be the lowest frequency day for Israel)
  • Is the increase in weekday messages due to paticular events, a result of technology, or simply a function of data curation.
  • Do different senders and recipients have different frequencies over time? Can these be tied to events?

Let’s look at State sending and receiving frequency, limited to essages that have some content in the subject, message body, and tags.

Who else are the major players? As in, who is sending/receiving lots of messages? Let’s look at top 1% in each direction. Note that if a given node is both a high frequency sender and a low frequency recipents, only the sender portion will be shown.

Topic models

First we look at smoothed topic prevalence. All topic model analysis is done on a 100 topic fit where each cable is represented by the text in its respective subject, message body, and content tags.

Since that might be too smooth, let’s look at prevalence aggregated monthly; scales are free since change in topic presence is more interesting than absoute presence.

Perhaps what’s more intersting is topic proportions over time; scales are free for the same reason as above.

What’s interesting about this is the relationships between administrative/policy topics and location/event topics. When the latter topics spike, the administrative topics decrease.
